When the `const` keyword is used at the end of a member function's signature in a class, it means that the function is a "constant member function." This const-qualification gives a specific guarantee: the member function will not modify any non-mutable member variables of the object on which it is called. In other words, calling this function will not change the state of the object, making it safe to call on `const` instances of the class.

Here is an example to illustrate:

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    MyClass(int value) : data(value) {}

    // A const member function, it promises not to modify the object
    int getValue() const {
        return data;
        // Any attempt to modify 'data' or any other member variable here would cause a compile error
    }

    // A non-const member function, it may modify the object
    void setValue(int value) {
        data = value;
    }

private:
    int data;
};

int main() {
    MyClass object(10);
    const MyClass constObject(20);

    std::cout << object.getValue() << std::endl; // Okay: object is non-const, getValue() is const-qualified
    std::cout << constObject.getValue() << std::endl; // Okay: getValue() can be called on a const instance

    object.setValue(30); // Okay: object is non-const
    // constObject.setValue(40); // Error: cannot call non-const member function on a const instance
}
```

In the example, `getValue()` is marked as `const`, indicating that it won't modify the object. Therefore, it can be called on both `const` and non-`const` instances of `MyClass`. On the other hand, the non-const function `setValue()` can only be called on non-`const` instances of `MyClass` since it's able to modify the object's state.

Attempting to call a non-const member function on a `const` object would result in a compile-time error because it may potentially violate the constness of the object. By using `const` correctly, you provide a strong interface contract about what functions will and won't alter the state of your objects, which helps catch bugs and design a clear API.

